</md></sn><sn><md>### PGF Equation{.text-center}

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-7
In one dimension, along the **x-axis**, the pressure gradient force ++per unit mass++ is:

$$
F_x = -\frac{1}{\rho} \frac{\Delta P}{\Delta x}
$$

+++ Where:

* $F_x$ = Pressure gradient force in the x-direction
* $\rho$ = air density
* $\Delta P$ = pressure difference obtained from isobar spacing
* $\Delta x$ = distance between isobars
* $\frac{d\rho}{dx}$ = change of pressure with distance
+++ 

* As $\text{PGF} \propto \frac{1}{\Delta x}$ , so the closer the isobar spacing the more increase is the pressure gradient force and greater the wind speed.
* **PGF** is inversely proportional to air density and this relationship has particular importance in understanding the vehavior of wind pattern.
:::

